There are a few places that I forget to take pictures of, and this is one of them!  We always gobble the food up so quickly!  They have yet to disappoint on taste or presentation, and is hands-down my favorite place to eat Pho!  The broth is perfection in a bowl, with just the right amount of soup to noodle ratio, with a generous amount of meat (I always order the combination Pho) and the side dish of fresh veggies (Thai basil, bean sprouts, Culantro, lemon wedges, and Jalapeno slices) which are always fresh.  The crispy deep-fried Spring rolls are also a favorite choice for me, with a wonderfully sweet, savory, and sour sauce as an accompaniment. Tonight, though, I chose to eat a wonderfully crispy, yet soft-breaded, Special sandwich, which included a plethora of meats topped with fresh and pickled veggies-- delicious!  The decor in the restaurant is charming and always clean.  The staff are friendly, work as a team, and the service is quick.  Best place EVER!

Pho Saigon serves some really good Vietnamese food and is definitely one of the nicer Vietnamese restaurants in town. I love their beef stew, so flavorful, and they have great pho and fried rice dishes, too. However, what really baffles me is the $16 price tag on their spring rolls. It's the only appetizer priced that high, all others are around $8. Spring rolls are a common dish found at any Vietnamese or Thai restaurant and they are always around $7 or $8, but $16?? I couldn't believe that price. What is up with that? It seems exorbitant. It's the one thing that bugs me about Pho Saigon. A friend of mine once ordered the spring rolls, and they're good, but not $16-good.

Updating review after visiting twice recently in Feb 2019. 4-5 stars staff/ service depending on who you get.  3-5 stars for taste depending what dish you order.  The fried egg rolls are pretty good, you actually get the aroma of crabmeat, black pepper, and garlic along with the usually expected for egg rolls.  The grilled pork in the bun bowl aren't true Vietnamese style/flavor. Instead of being marinated with lemon grass etc, they used the Chinese red pork flavoring ;/  I also had the rice dish (with grilled beef and shredded pork, good), and rare beef pho (good).  Mom REALLY like the beef stew (bo kho), and likes the chicken curry.  She also likes the duck leg in egg noodle soup bowl.  Prices are $3-4 higher than other Viet places, but it's nice, clean, aong with noticeably more protein (beef, pork, etc) in whatever you order. So it's worth it, and we'll be back since it's the only solid Viet place near Waikiki.
